# Here are the common LS_COLORS codes and their meanings:
#
# File Type Codes
# no: Normal (non-filename) text – default color
# fi: Regular file
# di: Directory
# ln: Symbolic link
# pi: Named pipe (FIFO)
# so: Socket
# bd: Block device
# cd: Character device
# or: Orphaned symbolic link (points to nonexistent file)
# mi: Missing file (nonexistent file referenced by symlink, shown in ls -l)
# ex: Executable file (has x permission)
# su: File with setuid bit (u+s)
# sg: File with setgid bit (g+s)
# st: Directory with sticky bit set (+t) and not world-writable
# ow: World-writable directory (o+w) and not sticky
# tw: World-writable and sticky directory (o+w,t)
#
# Special Codes
# lc: Left code (ANSI escape prefix)
# rc: Right code (ANSI escape suffix)
# ec: End code (resets color)
# *.ext: Color for files with extension .ext (e.g., *.txt, *.jpg)
# Color values are ANSI codes like 34 (blue), 42 (green background), or combined like 1;32 (bold green).
# These are defined in /etc/DIR_COLORS or ~/.dircolors and loaded via dircolors.
#
# ANSI Color Codes in LS_COLORS
# Text Attributes
# 00 – Default color
# 01 – Bold
# 04 – Underlined
# 05 – Flashing text
# 07 – Reverse (swap foreground/background)
# 08 – Concealed (hidden)
# Foreground Colors
# 30 – Black
# 31 – Red
# 32 – Green
# 33 – Yellow
# 34 – Blue
# 35 – Purple
# 36 – Cyan
# 37 – Grey
# 90–96 – Bright variants (e.g., 91 = light red)
# Background Colors
# 40 – Black background
# 41 – Red background
# 42 – Green background
# 43 – Yellow background
# 44 – Blue background
# 45 – Purple background
# 46 – Cyan background
# 47 – Grey background
# 100–106 – Bright background variants
# Examples
# 01;34 – Bold blue text (default for directories)
# 34;42 – Blue text on green background (world-writable dir)
# 30;42 – Black text on green background (ow)
# 38;5;160 – 256-color mode: foreground color 160
# 48;5;240 – 256-color mode: background color 240
# Colors are combined with semicolons and assigned to file types like di=01;34.

# dircolors -p > ~/.dircolors
# Edit ~/.dircolors, change OTHER_WRITABLE to a more readable color
# Then source it: eval "$(dircolors ~/.dircolors)"
# http://geoff.greer.fm/lscolors/